<subSubSection id="C5FB80EE9C761C3EED3CAD1D269DC7EF" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph id="93CE82217FF683DDBDBCF06FE9A1A895" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F18907805E1BFD0E86BB5CDC458C8F0C" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Body inflated, pentagonal (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C341DC8ABA787E8D2DC6189F26884C6D" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7a, b</figureCitation>
). Five short arms (some specimens may have 4-6 arms). Abactinal figs imbricated, decreasing in size towards the margin of the body, with 2-4 short, hyaline, divergent spines, which have the extremity trifurcate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BB5375615F0E225C25CD4BE0317F5606" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7c</figureCitation>
). Between each of these figs there is a papula (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B357656DE798243574AF51BF3B76A7C2" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7c</figureCitation>
). Anus located in the center of the abactinal surface. Superomarginal figs similar to the remaining abactinal figs, but with more numerous and slightly longer spines, forming a dense bundle (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B649CFD06BE1551A45D1413832C58A7B" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7a</figureCitation>
). Papulae restricted to the abactinal surface. Actinal figs similar to the abactinal figs, but a little bigger and longer, having 1-3 divergent spines, also similar to the dorsal ones, but slightly longer (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BFA95067C137E8E656A32F35303356A7" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7b</figureCitation>
). Inferomarginal figs similar to the remaining actinal figs. Adambulacral figs with three thin, vitreous, elongate spines (~0.035 mm), having the tips trifurcate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="377F2B78093183E8920A8E7E486C2128" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7d</figureCitation>
). Six thin, vitreous, elongate oral spines (~0.43 mm) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7F6889410A5657FC00163D6FA0617D28" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="793822031D5DF1A4C79124A6398B2345" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="CBC7064650080F035F31C504E5165B8B" bold="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Colour.</emphasis>
Juvenile specimens vary from white to cream-coloured, larger juveniles are yellow to reddish, while adults are blue or greenish-blue (
<bibRefCitation id="CEF01E6ABCE77BDE348AB6BECF727CE8" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="73EB93C8FD7976EBFF0CE6531FDBB225" author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 51" refId="B22" refString="Brito, IM, 1968. Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias. In: Boletim do Museu Nacional.: 1 - 51" title="Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias." volumeTitle="Boletim do Museu Nacional." year="1968">Brito (1968)</bibRefCitation>
recorded a dark grayish-blue for 25 specimens from Trindade Island (ES).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="336E94F30A739616AD9D4FA639BD798A" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="075ACDDBD42B78925DAA1292481701C0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B9D27BE75B6FD6CF12B3FFB6DD489B92" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Bermudas, Florida, Bahamas, Belize, Panama, and Brazil (
<bibRefCitation id="5FF43D441947A9A9F5B427519BD2F598" author="Verrill, AE" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin from the Laboratories of Natural History of the State University of Iowa" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 232" refId="B151" refString="Verrill, AE, 1915. Report on the starfishes of the West Indies, Florida, and Brazil, including those obtained by Bahamas Expedition from the University of Iowa in 1893. Bulletin from the Laboratories of Natural History of the State University of Iowa 7: 1 - 232" title="Report on the starfishes of the West Indies, Florida, and Brazil, including those obtained by Bahamas Expedition from the University of Iowa in 1893." volume="7" year="1915">Verrill 1915</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="AAB299FB125D337BBBF2875F0F10BBFF" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="D468CC98091DAEDE74FFB16F14E783EA" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="56337F68DFBF4836680923B97BED9F22" author="Alvarado, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="37 - 55" refId="B4" refString="Alvarado, JJ, Solis-Marin, FA, Ahearn, C, 2008. Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 56: 37 - 55" title="Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano." volume="56" year="2008">Alvarado et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="3C340A9861C4D06AD8CE1C89C3919218" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil: BA, RJ, and Trindade Island (
<bibRefCitation id="E42B3EC25AAC485984B3E2083E366B69" author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 10" refId="B21" refString="Brito, IM, 1962. Ensaio de catalogo dos equinodermas do Brasil. Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos: 1 - 10" title="Ensaio de catalogo dos equinodermas do Brasil" year="1962">Brito 1962</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="2E29EEB415DDFDEA68E4D3D92F612963" author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 51" refId="B22" refString="Brito, IM, 1968. Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias. In: Boletim do Museu Nacional.: 1 - 51" title="Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias." volumeTitle="Boletim do Museu Nacional." year="1968">1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="AB413A75220574DAEA851F39E24CAF44" author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Arquivos do Museu Nacional" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="261 - 265" refId="B23" refString="Brito, IM, 1971. Contribuicao ao conhecimento dos equinodermas da Ilha da Trindade. Arquivos do Museu Nacional 54: 261 - 265" title="Contribuicao ao conhecimento dos equinodermas da Ilha da Trindade." volume="54" year="1971">1971</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="226C14D2787ABE8BCA4A99851F9B8932" author="Oliveira, JP" journalOrPublisher="Scientia Plena" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 14" refId="B109" refString="Oliveira, JP, Oliveira, J, Manso, CLC, 2010. Inventario da colecao de equinodermos do LABIMAR, Campus Prof°. Alberto Carvalho, Universidade Federal de Sergipe. Scientia Plena 6: 1 - 14" title="Inventario da colecao de equinodermos do LABIMAR, Campus Prof °. Alberto Carvalho, Universidade Federal de Sergipe." volume="6" year="2010">Oliveira et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). In the presente study we record for the first time its presence in the State of 
<normalizedToken id="5313B8B36440414E074AC4516E31854D" originalValue="Paraíba">Paraiba</normalizedToken>
. Intertidal to 15 m in depth (
<bibRefCitation id="D8159C05F74E358A64FF184DDAFEE318" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6100A537732CCA90A2E6996C6BEDA3F6" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="6D7049F2842D32209FE2B0BA26DE944A" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5D85DB697344B2686D5FC5CB695D39D" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Only two species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A36671031AD2FD92287D00C730E3D298" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1913" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E66F715FBB8C081852C3D3C12772A65E" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known from the Atlantic Ocean, 
<taxonomicName id="8CAE6E16B40D3815FB897A3F6C01F30D" baseAuthorityName="Luetken" baseAuthorityYear="1860" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides folium" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="folium">
<emphasis id="CCAD314513C3B6AF0472DDE1CB224679" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides folium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DC71A6E4C9D8DC73B44EF65D889A18EB" baseAuthorityName="Döderlein" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides hartmeyeri" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="hartmeyeri">
<emphasis id="EA7F144BECC1E591C2071ECB32C99D88" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides hartmeyeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="9A7D66016718D0E45DDA8F21CC2A2D69" originalValue="Döderlein">Doederlein</normalizedToken>
, 1910). The first is recorded for Bermudas and southern Brazil and the second only for the Caribbean region. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="9BBABFE6DF51EFC147F0D1DDC5D42A66" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
these species are partially sympatric, and for this reason have previously easily been confused with each other. In a revision of family 
<taxonomicName id="3332B8BD0E58D3E4BA51FCCFBED21635" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Spinulosida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Asterinidae</taxonomicName>
based on molecular and morphological data, 
<bibRefCitation id="C3148F82F6FC5F5B0A793BFD0064A12A" author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of Museum Victoria" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 40" refId="B111" refString="O'Loughlin, PM, Waters, JM, 2004. A molecular and morphological revision of genera of Asterinidae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea). Memoirs of Museum Victoria 61: 1 - 40" title="A molecular and morphological revision of genera of Asterinidae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea)." volume="61" year="2004">
<normalizedToken id="3F70D676F05AF3F1F06C3548E9896934" originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
and Waters (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
transferred 
<taxonomicName id="B2F718A0305B62B044E64ED53503F910" baseAuthorityName="Luetken" baseAuthorityYear="1860" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides folium" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="folium">
<emphasis id="A214AA1085E48560599483166832A8C4" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides folium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FC06105C9A17C58DE84879A4B2718608" baseAuthorityName="Döderlein" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides hartmeyeri" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="hartmeyeri">
<emphasis id="61FA9B2CFFF4A84E57F15BD32B5CB7A4" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides hartmeyeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A793E85CB8293980C96C92CE146AA389" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterina" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterina" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C108D08BA2D13AC95535A40209347790" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="25772BFD3359E30459492043B7E9CDD7" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1913" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="39C854B41B35BB69CC3CC98D32A95F35" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, remarking on the morphological similarities between these two species. 
<taxonomicName id="81AF535D08CE6DEDDE8C6771F90CA34F" baseAuthorityName="Luetken" baseAuthorityYear="1860" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides folium" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="folium">
<emphasis id="316F7A3861F342CFB48AD1CE44DAF765" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides folium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="A86F4508F4428E17B9A2CF234D3292A1" baseAuthorityName="Döderlein" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Asterinides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asterinides hartmeyeri" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="hartmeyeri">
<emphasis id="954CF102B98C430C3C05DD8479D3C88A" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asterinides hartmeyeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for having bigger papular pores, 6 to 7 series of actinal figs and abactinal figs arranged into two rows. A broad discussion of the main differences between these two species is given by 
<bibRefCitation id="3C704EC2EDDB2BFFC0E0881F927C61AC" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="6A3357066CBC7FF3717FBAF5DDEA53B8" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, this species rarely reaches 2.5 cm in diameter. Specimens examined in this study had a larger ray (R, maximum of 7.76 mm) and differed from those described by Hendler (op cit.) for not having narrow radial areas inflated, having instead the abactinal surface completely inflated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8AE6EA4D6A1C4F493FB9AFE3ED076304" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="ecological notes">
<paragraph id="5AD16AC308C99E294DD9D6A42AC2879E" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3A503E0266059C46D991DDFA5091875E" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This species lives in association with coral reefs, being found particularly under rocks or corals of the reef flat (
<bibRefCitation id="A096263206B73B0CF66EE0531886A084" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen from 
<normalizedToken id="EFE4A8965C8963FDB0F1137AE086DD92" originalValue="Paraíba">Paraiba</normalizedToken>
recorded in this study was found associated with rhodolite beds at 10 m depth. Although the species is reported from several localities, is has never been found in large numbers (
<bibRefCitation id="3408E18AF6F0D1D0F914A0B722DAAFEE" author="Hendler, G" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B55" refString="Hendler, G, Miller, JE, Pawson, DL, Kier, PM, 1995. Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" title="Sea stars, sea urchins and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean." year="1995">Hendler et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="809944D1F691C07660CB8B2213CBF315" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Only 
<bibRefCitation id="20DF4C97E40ABA896D39A6C1E8F5935B" author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Arquivos do Museu Nacional" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="261 - 265" refId="B23" refString="Brito, IM, 1971. Contribuicao ao conhecimento dos equinodermas da Ilha da Trindade. Arquivos do Museu Nacional 54: 261 - 265" title="Contribuicao ao conhecimento dos equinodermas da Ilha da Trindade." volume="54" year="1971">Brito (1971)</bibRefCitation>
observed this species to be relatively abundant mainly under rocks at Trindade Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
